Date: 21 Jun 2002 12:29 PM ES
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: De Telegraaf, 19 Jun 2002 [Translated from Dutch, edited]
<http://archief.telegraaf.nl/artikel.pl?id=253916&pagina=0&query=Zeehonden&datumsort=on&bron=alles>
Seals virus reaches the Waddenzee
-----------------------------------
The Hague: The first seal with the so-called phocine distemper virus or
"Seal disease" has been found in Vlieland. This virus is very infectious
for seals, but is not dangerous for humans; this has been announced by The
Ministry of Agriculture, Nature Management and Fisheries on Wed 19 Jun 2002.
The seal was found on Sun 16 Jun 2002 by a collaborator of the Seal
Rehabilitation and Research Center, Pieterburen, and brought over to the
Center. Following a virological investigation it was shown on Wednesday
that the virus is the same one which has been causing,since May
2002,harbor-seal mortality in Danish and Swedish waters.
Since seals can swim 150 km a day, it was expected that the virus would
emerge in the Waddenzee. The same virus caused in 1988 major mortality in
European seals.
The seal from Vlieland has died in the meantime.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Vlieland is one of the five inhabited Dutch "Frisian" isles separated from
the mainland by the Dutch Wadden Sea (Waddenzee). During the previous major
outbreak in 1988 and thereafter, the Center in Pieterburen was one of the
institutes actively involved in the research, cooperating with other North
European centres.
An examination of the long-term dynamic consequences of the 1988 epizootic
of phocine distemper virus (PDV) infection in Northern European common seal
populations, carried out by the Department of Zoology, Cambridge
University, UK [See "Quantitative investigations of the epidemiology of
phocine distemper virus (PDV) in European common seal populations" by
B.T.Grenfell, M.E. Lonergan and J.Harwood in Sci Total Environ 1992 Apr
20;115(1-2):15-29], led to the conclusion that a reintroduction of the
virus would be unlikely to cause an outbreak on the scale of the 1988
epizootic until the seal population had recovered for at least 10 years. -
Mod.AS]
